<subSubSection id="66F26515BC547064D0C8F9A8FE77DC6B" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="2E57369EBC547064D0C8F9A8FC4FDD84" blockId="54.[151,1436,1650,1929]" box="[199,973,1650,1674]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis id="1C9CEA8CBC547064D0C8F9A8FECFDD84" bold="true" box="[199,333,1650,1674]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named for its occurrence in saline habitat.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E57369EBC547064D0C8F94CFE77DC6B" blockId="54.[151,1436,1650,1929]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis id="1C9CEA8CBC547064D0C8F94CFEA8DDA1" bold="true" box="[199,298,1686,1711]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" reason="1">Habitat.</emphasis>
Apparently restricted to saline habitats. This is the only water mite and one of the most commonly collected invertebrate species in saline streams along the Persian Gulf. The associated fauna includes the snail species 
<emphasis id="1C9CEA8CBC547064D0C6F904FE3DDDF8" box="[201,447,1758,1782]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Cerithidaea cingulata</emphasis>
(Gmelin) and 
<taxonomicName id="E9E84D1DBC547064D26EF904FD60DDF8" box="[609,738,1758,1782]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Ecrobia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="1C9CEA8CBC547064D26EF904FD38DDF8" box="[609,698,1758,1782]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Ecrobia</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
, which are characteristic for brackish waters (Glöer &amp; Pešić in prep.). We did not measure the salinity during our field work but most probably this species has a high salinity tolerance, as it is able to inhabit saturated brine (
<figureCitation id="B6D32A1BBC547064D295F8F3FC81DC4F" box="[666,771,1833,1857]" captionStart="FIGURE 44" captionStartId="60.[151,250,1863,1886]" captionTargetBox="[179,1411,179,1836]" captionTargetId="figure-98@60.[179,1411,169,1840]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="FIGURE 44A–D. Running water habitats: A — saline stream near Khorgoo village (locus typicus of Haloaxonopsis salina); B — the shallow stream N of Bandar Abbass (locus typicus of Nilotonia hormozgana and Axonopsis gloeeri); C — stream in Banglayan village (locus typicus of Torrenticola asadiae, T. hormozganus, Monatractides martini and Neoatractides calidus); D — Rudan stream (locus typicus of Atractides hormozganus, Javalbia persica, Axonopsis interstitialis, A. hyporheica, and Albia hyporheica). Photos. V. Pešić." pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 44A</figureCitation>
). The weel-like acetabula should be considered as an adaptation to the salty environment.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
